ANTHRAX - ARGENTINA (02): (BUENOS AIRES) BOVINE
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 21 Feb 2013
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


A herd of 120 cross-bred Angus x Hereford cattle was grazing [in Laprida, Buenos Aires Province] a single pasture with very little vegetation supplemented latterly with grain. The zone had suffered excessive flooding during the 2012 winter. This farm had had no anthrax outbreaks in the previous 30 years, and the stock had not been vaccinated.

During the last week (10-16 Feb 2013), 9 animals died suddenly, 5 cows and 4 calves at heel. All suffered acute deaths with blood extravasation from natural openings, made worse by scavenging birds feeding on their eyes.

This event was reported to the Veterinary Services, and the carcasses were handled in the traditional manner by covering them with lime and then with a thick plastic tarpaulin weighted down along its margins. An Epidemiologic Alert was issued when one of the farm gauchos developed a skin lesion after skinning one of the calves. Such reports to the national authority SENASA are obligatory since 1930.

--
Ramon Noseda
CFO-Director/Microbiologist
Laboratorio Azul Diagnostico S.A.
Av. 25 de Mayo 479
(B 7300 FXE) Azul Bs. As.
