[Our thanks, yet again, to Ramon for this report. I apologise for the delay in posting, but I have been on the road.

Normally, one doesn't see anthrax with calves, mainly because they are suckling, not grazing, but these calves will have been some 7 months old. How these animals acquired their infections is not obvious, as the estancia had been free for some 30 years. One can propose that the winter flooding transported buried spores up to the soil surface, but then why the delay in onset?

My rancher friends tell me that they see outbreaks in their animals when it has been hot and dry -- which stresses the animals -- but usually around 10 days after a brief shower. This shower allows the short grazing to sprout, making it very attractive to graze, and the rain will have loosened the soil, ensuring that it is ingested along with the grazing, as cattle tug their feed out of the ground with their tongues. Normally, cattle eat 5-6 lbs of soil each day when the soil is loose enough to release the forage roots. The only other explanation would be that they were receiving contaminated bone meal in their feed supplement. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1yJb, http://healthmap.org/r/1yJb.]
